To understand why password algorithms use RAM, imagine a hacker's GPU as a massive factory with 5,000 tiny workers (processing cores).
Testing a SHA-256 hash: The math is so simple that each worker can do it entirely in their head. 
All 5,000 workers can guess passwords at the exact same time without stopping.
Testing an Argon2id hash: The algorithm forces each worker to fill out a massive notebook of random data (e.g., 64 Megabytes of data) before they can finish the math.
They cannot do it in their head; they must use a desk (RAM) to lay out the notebook.
Because a GPU only has a limited amount of total memory ("desk space"), there is only enough room for, say, 10 notebooks at a time.
The other 4,990 workers must sit idly and wait for a desk to clear.By forcing the math to require memory, the algorithm destroys the hacker's biggest advantage

